<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-420-533  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 420 533.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Motorola unveils Iridium, a global communications system.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Motorola Inc. (planning).andO;Ticker:    MOT.andO;Topic:     Cellular radioPlanningTelecommunicationsTelecommunications ServicesSatellite Communications.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MOTOROLA UNVEILS IRIDIUM, A GLOBAL COMMUNICATIONS SYSTEM NEW YORK, NEW YORK,U.S.A., 1990 JUN 26 (NB) -- Amid great fanfare and press coverage Motorolaannounced a global communications system that will allow people tocommunicate by telephone anywhere on earth -- whether on land, at sea or inthe air -- via portable cellular radio telephones operating as part of asatellite-based system.andP;  Callers using the new system will not need to knowthe location of the person being called; they will simply dial that person'snumber to be connected.andM;Estimated cost for the new system, which Motorola calls Iridium, is $2.1billion.andP;  Phones used to access it were estimated by the company to cost$3,000 each.andM;The company has established a satellite communications business unit todevelop Iridium.andP;  The heart of Iridium will be a network of 77 satellites inlow-earth orbit, working together as a digital switched communicationsnetwork in space.andP;  The system will be able to handle both voice and data.andM;European operations for Iridium will be based in Scotland, where the companyis building a $160 million facility which will make equipment for Europe,employing 2,000.andP;  The director of the Scottish Development Agency, NorthAmerica, Robert Crawford, said Iridium &quot;could significantly accelerate thecommunications linkup between all regions of Europe and facilitate the 1992process of making Europe a much greater economic entity and marketplace.&quot;andM;American Mobile Satellite, meanwhile, signed a memorandum of understandingwith Motorola to jointly explore the potential of Iridium.andP;  The two companieswill jointly analyze the technical and business issues involved.andP;  Motorolaneeds such deals, as well as financing, to make the multi-billion dollarIridium project fly.andM;But a statement from George Tellmann, chief executive officer of AMSC, wasfilled with qualifiers concerning the feasibility of Iridium.andP;  &quot;AMSC, as thepremier U.S.andP;  mobile satellite carrier, is intrigued by the Iridium concept,&quot;he said.andP;  &quot;If the concept can be brought to fruition, it could enable AMSC'sNorth American customers to access a global system for personal satellitecommunications.&quot; AMSC was licensed by the Federal Communications Commission ayear ago to launch and operate the mobile satellite system for the entireU.S.andP;  AMSC will begin providing mobile data services late this year vialeased capacity on an existing satellite; full voice and high-speed dataservices will begin with the launch of AMSC's first satellite in 1993.andM;The current projection for the introduction of the Iridium system fits wellwith AMSC's strategic planning for future system enhancements, the companysaid.andP;  Telesat Mobile of Canada and the International Maritime SatelliteOrganization, which provides communications for ships and aircraft, will alsostudy the system, the latter as a possible successor to its existing networkfor linking planes in flight.andM;Generally, reaction to the Iridium announcement was guarded.andP;  Critics notedthe company will need financial help, frequency allocations from the FCC andother regulators worldwide, and cooperation from competitors.andP;  Conventionalcellular systems are being installed rapidly around the world, and by thetime Iridium opens for business most of those will be high-capacity digitalsystems under the TDMA scheme on which, ironically, Motorola claims somepatent rights.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900629/Press Contact: Ruth Pritchard-Kelly, AmericanMobile Satellite, 202-331-5858; The Scottish Development Agency, MaryMorrissey, 617-536-3003; Motorola, Lawrence Moore, 602/441-3000)</TEXT></DOC>